So let's first set $(x+2)(x-3)=14$ and expand the left hand side. We find that $(x^2-x-6)=14$. We rewrite the right hand side as $14$ so the equation becomes $x^2-x-6-14=0$, or $x^2-x-20=0$, so we write it out to get $x^2-x-20=0$. From here we see that $a=1$, $b = -1$, and $c = -20$. Now we know from the quadratic formula that if $a$, $b$, and $c$ are coefficients of a quadratic equation, then the solutions are
 \begin{align*}
 \frac{-b \pm \sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}
\end{align*}
 so we plug in the numbers and simplify:
 \begin{align*}
 \frac{-(-1) \pm \sqrt{(-1)^2-4(1)(-20)}}{2(1)} & = \frac{1 \pm \sqrt{1+80}}{2} \\
 & = \frac{1 \pm \sqrt{81}}{2} \\
 & = \frac{1 \pm 9}{2} \\
 x & = \frac{1 \pm 9}{2} \\
 x & = \frac{1 + 9}{2}, \frac{1 - 9}{2} \\
 x & = 5, \frac{-8}{2} \\
 x & = 5, -4
\end{align*}
To get the product we compute $(5)(-4) = \boxed{-20}$</answer>

